                  Asia Stocks to Watch
              




Why Goldman Sachs is Bullish on These Energy Stocks


 








By

Robert Guy



        July 24, 2017 4:50 a.m. ET
      


 














Text Size
Regular
Medium
Large



 

















 Goldman Sachs is bullish on India's oil marketing companies (OMCs) as they look cheap against their global peers and could be set for a re-rating. 












 India's oil marketing companies - which operate refineries and service stations, and sell a range of products from jet fuel to lubricants  - are seeing their marketing businesses trade at an enterprise value-to-EBITDA multiple of 6 times compared to 10 times for their global peers, says the broker. Goldman Sachs has added Bharat Petroleum (500547.IN), which is rated buy, to its conviction list. Here's why it's so bullish on the stock, which has a price target of INR585 a share. BPCL shares have lagged peer Indian oil marketing companies (OMCs) by 25% in the last 12 months driven by weaker than expected earnings in the last 3 quarters due to Kochi start-up costs. However, we believe this underperformance will reverse in next 12 months as (1) refining earnings pick up from 2HFY18E given ongoing Kochi upgrade/expansion and (2) OMC multiples re-rate higher as investors give more credit for diminishing regulatory headwinds (move towards daily/dynamic pricing), structurally rising retail volume growth with optionality of higher marketing margins longer-term. Goldman Sachs also upgraded Hindustan Petroleum (500104.IN) to buy from neutral. The broker, which has a sum-of-the-parts-based price target of INR450 a share, reckons the multiple for the fuel retailing business could re-rate on less regulatory headwinds, rising volume growth, and possibility of higher marketing margins: We upgrade HPCL to Buy from Neutral with 22% potential upside to our  revised 12-month SOTP-based target price of Rs450 (from Rs363.33). We like HPCL’s exposure to the fuel retailing business (highest amongst the  OMCs as of FY17) and it also has the highest sensitivity to changes in marketing margins and changes in valuation multiple for the marketing business, where it has the highest EBITDA contribution. Bharat Petroleum last traded down 0.3% to INR465.90 a share, while Hindustan Petroleum was up 0.7% to INR370.70 a share.


 

















Text Size
Regular
Medium
Large



 






gas


Goldman Sachs


oil


refining


